text: World Wide Web https://doi.org/10.1007/s11280-018-0560-7 Direction-based vacancy queries in camera sensor networks Xi Guo1,2 · Xiaochun Yang3 · Huaijie Zhu4 · Yakun Bu5 Received: 19 August 2017 / Revised: 22 March 2018 / Accepted: 1 April 2018 © Springer Science+Business Media, LLC, part of Springer Nature 2018 Abstract In a camera sensor network, given a target q and a set of cameras P, q may not be recognized by P due to its facing direction even if every pi ∈ P can see q. In this paper, we study the direction-based vacancy query, which can find out the vacant direction ranges where q cannot be recognized by any cameras. If q’s facing direction fq is far from the sensing direction of a camera, i.e., the included angle between the two directions is smaller than θ , q cannot be effectively recognized due to the vacancy of cameras on the direction fq. To answer vacancy queries, the basic algorithm is to sort the directions of all cameras P and then to identify the vacant ranges. design an index structure, i.e., α-polygon tree, which can organize the objects according to their directions. To make the tree as balance as possible, we propose an algorithm to select the best splitter for each tree node when building the tree. Our tree-based algorithm is to shrink the vacancy ranges while visiting the tree nodes in a depth-first order. The tree nodes are pruned if they do not contain objects (i.e., cameras) that may make the vacancy ranges shrink. We conducted experiments to evaluate the performances of the α-polygon tree and the tree-based query algorithm on both synthetic and real datasets. Keywords Direction-based query · Vacant direction · α-polygon tree · Index optimization · Camera sensor network The directional sensor has a sector sensing range, which is different from the omni-angle sensing range of the isotropic sensor. The common directional sensors are cameras, ultra- sonic sensors and infrared sensors. Directional sensor networks have a wide range of applications, such as security monitoring, precision farming, battlefield surveillance, and so on. Among abundant literatures of directional sensor networks ([2, 7], etc.), some interest- ing problems arise if we consider the facing directions of targets. As Figure 1a shows, the camera sensor p1 cannot effectively recognize the target q due to q’s facing direction fq, even if p1 can see q which falls into its sensing range scopep1. A target can be effectively recognized if it can be identified from its pictures or videos taken by the cameras, however, the facing direction of the target is critical for the identification. For example, it is easy to distinguish a person by his face while it is difficult to distinguish a person by the back side of his head. To capture this characteristic, [4] introduces the effective-sensing model, and the subsequent studies ([6, 13], and etc.) focus on scheduling cameras in order to maximize the continuous monitoring time.

A camera sensor p can effectively recognize a targetq if its sensing direction qp is close to the facing direction fq of the target, i.e., the included angle between qp and fq is smaller than θ , where θ is the angular threshold for correct identifications. As Figure 1a shows, camera p2 can effectively recognize q because the included angle between p2’s sensing direction qp2 and q’s facing direction fq is smaller than θ , but another camera p1 cannot effectively recognize q, because the included angle between qp1 and fq is larger than θ . In Figure 1 Effectively recognize targets by camera sensors Traditional spatial indexing methods, such as point quad-tree, R∗-tree, and so on [3], cannot index objects according to their relative directions. In this paper, we propose an α- polygon tree to organize objects according to their directions. Every tree node stores an object p ∈ P, andp divides the tree node into m child nodes. Each child node is in charge of an α-polygon, which covers α degrees w.r.t. p. The progressive approach visits the cam- eras from the root node, and enlarges the recognizable ranges with respect to (w.r.t.) the objects visited. The tree nodes that cannot enlarge the recognizable ranges should be pruned. The progressive approach terminates when there is no tree nodes remained unvisited or the recognizable range reaches [0◦, 360◦). In addition, to make the α-polygon tree as balance as possible, we propose an approach to find the best splitter of each tree node. We con- duct experiments to evaluate the performances of the vacancy queries on both synthetic and real datasets. The experimental results show that by the supports of the α-polygon tree the pro- gressive approach runs much faster than the baseline approach. In addition, if we optimize the α-polygon tree and make it balance, the progressive approach can perform better.

A recognizable range of a camera p is the angular range (φp ↓ θ, φp ↑ θ), whereφ p denotes the polar angle1 of qp and φp ↑ θ (or φp ↓ θ ) denotes the angle of qp rotating θ anticlockwise (or clockwise). As Figure 1b shows, if q’s facing (cid:5), which is outside of any recognizable range, q cannot be recognized due direction is fq (cid:5). All cameras pi’s have their recognizable ranges, and the to the vacancy of cameras on fq remaining ranges are the vacant ranges. Identifying the vacant ranges is very important in security monitoring applications, because a trespasser q can escape from being monitored by facing a vacant direction deliberately. Due to security concerns it is better to recognize the target no matter which direction it faces. In this paper, we study the direction-based vacancy query which aims at finding the vacant ranges. Given the target q and a set of camera sensors P that can see q, the vacancy query is to find the vacant ranges where no camera can effectively recognize q. To answer the vacancy query, the basic approach is to sort the cameras in the ascending order of their sensing directions. The vacant range may exist in the gap between two neighbouring sensing directions. If the length of the gap is larger than 2θ, the vacant range exists. The basic approach can answer the vacancy query well when there are a small number of targets and cameras. An exemplary scenario is to monitor the persons in a room using several cameras. However, the basic approach becomes time consuming when there are a large number of targets and cameras. In public places, for example, the airport should monitor thousands of persons by using hundreds of cameras. It is better to find the cameras which can see the target, and then identify the vacant ranges. To answer vacancy queries fast in such scenarios, we propose the progressive approach, which is supported by an index of the cameras. Contributions In this paper, we propose the vacancy query problem in the camera sensor network (CSN). Our detailed contributions are as follows.

– We propose the vacancy query to find the vacant ranges where the target cannot be effectively recognized by cameras (Section 2.1), and design a basic algorithm to answer the vacancy queries for small CSNs (Section 2.2). – We propose a progressive algorithm for large CSNs, which is supported by the α- polygon tree (Section 3). In the space IR2, given a target q, there are a set of cameras P which can see q. Definition 1 (Camera in Charge) A camera p is in charge of a target q, if q is within the sensing range of p, which is a sector scopep. sensing angle ψ of cameras. Definition 2 (Sensing Direction) The sensing direction of a camera p ∈ P w.r.t. the target q is the polar angle φp in the polar coordinate system, where the pole is q and the polar axis Lq is the ray starting from q and being parallel to the positive x-axis. Generally speaking, any ray from q can act as the polar axis Lq . In this paper, we set the ray parallel to the positive x-axis to be Lq . When there is no ambiguity, we simply say the “direction” of p instead of the “sensing direction” of p. As Figure 2a shows, the camera p has a sensing range scopep which depends on the parameters ψ and r of the camera sensor. Since the target q falls into scopep, p is in charge of q. The sensing direction of p is denoted by the polar angle φp.

Definition 3 (Effectively Recognition) When the target q faces a direction ω ∈ [0◦, 360◦), it can be effectively recognized by the camera p ∈ P, if the angular difference between ω and φp is smaller than θ , where φp is the direction of p and θ is the identification threshold. As Figure 2b shows, assuming that the identifi- cation threshold θ = 30◦, ifq ’s facing direction ω1, q can be effectively recognized because |ω1 − φp| < θ. In other words, ω1 is a recognizable direction due to the existence of cam- era p. However, if q’s facing direction is ω2, q cannot be effectively recognized because |ω2 − φp| > θ. In other words, q is unrecognisable due to the vacancy of cameras on the direction ω2. Definition 4 (Vacant Direction) Given a target q with its facing direction ω and a set of cameras P in charge of q, ifq cannot be effectively recognized by all the cameras P, i.e., |ω − φpi| > θ (∀pi ∈ P), the direction ω is a vacant direction. Problem 1 (Direction-Based Vacancy Query) Given a target q and the cameras P in charge of q, the direction-based vacancy query, denoted as vacant(P, q, θ), is to find the set of vacant direction ranges V = {V1, V2, . . . , Vk}, whereω ∈ Vi is a vacant direction. As Figure 2c shows, even if q can be seen by the cameras {p1, p2, p3}, q cannot be effectively recognized if it faces a direction in the vacant range V1 or the vacant range V2. We will introduce how to find the vacancy ranges in next section.

In Algorithm 1, we initialize the vacant range set V as empty (line 1). We compute the direction of each camera pi ∈ P w.r.t. the target q, and add each direction into the set (cid:7) (lines 3 to 5). Due to wide application ranges of wireless sensor networks ([8, 9], etc.), various coverage problems arise and attract lots of concerns [14]. In recent years, the developments of mul- timedia technologies make the camera sensors cheaper and more easily deployed, and thus the camera sensor networks becomes pervasive ([2, 7], etc.). Different from the isotropic sensors that have omnidirectional coverages, camera sensors have sector coverages and also have some unique properties consequently. One property is a camera cannot effectively rec- ognize a target due to the target’s facing direction even if the camera can see the target. In [4], Hong et al. propose the effective-sensing model which captures this unique property, and they design a heuristic algorithm to solve the ML-EPT problem (i.e., maximum lifetime effective-sensing partial target-coverage problem). The ML-EPT problem is to schedule the active periods of cameras in order to make the effective-covered weight is at least W at any moment and the CSN working time is maximized. The effective-covered weight is the total weight of targets that can be effectively recognized. The weight of a target is used to measure the importance of the target.

Based on the effective-sensing model, [5] studies the DCP-MCSN problem (i.e., desper- ate coverage problem in mission-driven camera sensor networks). The DCP-MCSN problem is to schedule the active periods of cameras w.r.t. the primary objective and the secondary objective. The primary objective is to maximize the number of fully-covered targets who have the highest monitoring priorities. A fully-covered target should always be effectively recognized during the mission period. The secondary objective is to maximize the over- all target-temporal coverage of unimportant targets. A temporal-covered target should be effectively recognized in a time interval during the mission period. Hong et al. [6] extends DCP-MCSN problem and studies the scheduling problems when the camera sensors are adjustable. Hong et al. [4–6] focus on scheduling the active periods of the camera sensors with effective-sensing model, while Singh et al. [11] study the scheduling problems in the direction adjustment aspect. Instead of scheduling the active periods of cameras, [11] deter- mines the sensing directions of cameras in order to maximize the CSN working time. They propose a column generation algorithm to solve the problem and the algorithm is improved in [13] by using three heuristics. In our paper, the vacancy query problem is inspired by the effective-sensing model of cameras, however, it is different from the scheduling problems, which focus on how to deploy a CSN. Our problem aims at identifying the vacant ranges of the target w.r.t. a deployed CSN, rather than a CSN being deployed.

In this paper, we propose the α-polygon tree to support vacancy queries. The α-polygon tree is a variation of the point quad-tree [3]. The point quad-tree divides the space into four quadrants recursively. Each tree node is restricted to store one object at most. The shape of the point quad-tree depends on the order in which the objects are inserted. The average time of searching for an object in the quad-tree is O(log4 n) if the objects are inserted randomly. To improve the efficiency of searching, [3] proposes an algorithm to make the quad-tree as balance as possible. The algorithm sorts the objects primarily by one key and secondarily by the other key. The object in the middle of the sorted list is selected to be the root of tree. The remaining objects are grouped into four subsets which will form the four sub- trees of the root node. The procedure of selecting the middle object is used recursively on the four subsets. However, the precondition of the algorithm is all the objects are known a priori. Overmars and van Leeuwen [10] proposes an algorithm to make the quad-tree balance dynamically. When inserting a new object, the algorithm checks the predefined balance criterion. If the insertion causes a violation of the balance criterion, the tree should be rebalanced partially. In this paper, we also propose an optimization method to make the α-polygon tree balance. Since the space is divided into α-polygons rather than the four quadrants, we cannot use the existing algorithms. Our algorithm is to rotate the split lines and make the objects distribute as evenly as possible in the α-polygons. To the best of our knowledge, rotating split lines is a new method that has not been proposed yet. To make the vacancy query more efficient, we propose a data structure called α-polygon tree, which can organize the objects (i.e., camera sensors) P according to their directions. The α-polygon tree is an m-ary search tree. Generally speaking, it is a variation of the traditional point quad-tree [3]. The difference is that the α-polygon tree subdivides the space into α-polygons, while the quad-tree subdivides the space into equal-sized grid cells.

Like the point quad-tree, each tree node in the α-polygon tree can only store one object, and the object also acts as a splitter to subdivide the tree node into m child nodes, where m = 360◦ α . Each child node is in charge of an α-polygon. Specially, the root node is in charge of the whole space. Definition 5 (α-polygon) The α-polygon is a polygon bounded by two rays (r1 and r2) from a given pole p, if the polar angle difference between r1 and r2 is α. For example, in Figure 4, given the splitting angle α = 60◦, the object A is stored in the root node, and it also acts as a splitter which subdivides the whole space into six α- polygons. Among them, there are three α-polygons contain objects. The child nodes are created recursively until there is no object in any sub-polygon of the current tree node. The object B falls into the 1st α-polygon of the root node, thus a new child node T2 are created to store B. Since there is no objects in the sub-polygons of T2, T2 becomes a leaf node. The object D falls into the 3rd α-polygon of the root node, and a child node T3 is created to store object D. T3 also becomes a leaf node. The object C falls into the 5th α-polygon of the root Figure 4 The α-polygon tree node, and a child node T4 is created to store object C. Recursively, object E falls into the 2nd α-polygon of T4, and a child node T5 is created to store E.

To build an α-polygon tree T , the objects pi ∈ P can be inserted into T one by one in an arbitrary order. When inserting an object pi, we search pi in the tree and descend to the lowest α-polygon it falls into. If the tree is empty, we should create a root node to store pi. If the tree is not empty, assuming we have descended to the lowest polygon that is the j -th polygon of a tree node Ti, we should create a new node to store pi and make the new node to be the j -the child node of Ti. In Figure 4, we insert the objects in the alphabetical order. First, we insert the object A and it would to be stored the root node T1. Since T1 is the root node, it is in charge of the whole space. The whole space is divided into six α-polygons by regarding A as the pole. The next object inserted is the object B. It falls into the 1st sub- polygon of T1. We create a new tree node T1 to store B, and make T2 the child node of T1. The tree node T2 is in charge of the 1st sub-polygon of T1. The sub-polygon is divided into six α-polygons by regarding B as the pole. In the same way, we insert the remaining objects {C, D, E} in to the tree.

Algorithm 2 shows the procedure of constructing the α-polygon tree. Each tree node node (as well as the root node root) has two attributes, i.e., node.p and node.polygons. The attribute node.p stores the coordinates of the object p. The attribute node.polygons is an array of node pointers, which consists of m elements, namely, node.polygons[0] to node.polygons[m − 1]. The element node.polygons[i] stores the pointer of a child node of node, which corresponds to the ith sub-polygon w.r.t. the pole node.p. The objects in P are inserted into the tree one by one (lines 2 to 22). If the tree is empty, we create the root node root (lines 3 to 5). Otherwise, we insert an object p following two steps. The first step is to search the lowest α-polygon which p falls into (lines 7 to 16). At lines 9 to 10, we compute the direction φp of p w.r.t. the splitter node.p, and then determine the identifier polyI D of the sub-polygon p falling into. If the polygon contains no object, the node.polygons[polyI D] is N U LL, and we terminate the loop (lines 11 to 12). Otherwise, we descend to the child pointed by node.polygons[polyI D] and continue searching the α-polygon where p falls into. After the searching phase finishes, we go to step 2. The 2nd step is to create a new node to store p (lines 17 to 19) and to insert it into the tree (line 20). The average time of inserting a tree node is O(logm n) if the tree is balance, where m is the number of child nodes of a tree node. Thus, the time complexity of Algorithm 2 is O(n logm n) and m is usually a small constant number.

The α-polygon tree should be updated when an object is added into P or an object is removed from P. When a new object p is added into P, we should insert a new tree node to store p. We search for the suitable place to insert the new tree node from the root node. If p falls into the j th sub-polygon of the root node, we check whether a child node in charge of this sub-polygon exists. If the child node exists, we descend to the child node and repeat the checking procedure recursively, because in the α-polygon tree each tree node should only store one object. If the corresponding child node does not exist, it means that we have found the suitable place to insert p, and a new child node is created to store p. When an object pi ∈ P is removed from P, we should delete the tree node of pi from the α-polygon tree too. The basic approach is to find the tree node Tj that stores pi. Next, we retrieve the objects storing in the sub-tree of Tj and keep these objects in a temporary array. Then the tree node Tj and its sub-tree are deleted. At last, the objects in the temporary array are reinserted into the tree. We only discuss the basic approach for deleting a tree node in this paper, since the delete operation is beyond the scope of this paper and it is a complicated problem even if for quad-trees [12]. The shape of the α-polygon tree depends on the insertion order of objects. To make the searches on the tree faster, it would be better to make the tree as balance as pos- sible. Let s denote the object stored in a tree node T and P denote the objects stored in the sub-tree of T . Ideally, by regarding p as the pole, each sub-polygon of T con- tains the same number of objects. Such object s is the best splitter of P . When building the α-polygon tree for objects P, we can assign the insertion order beforehand to make the tree balance if P are known a priori. At best, the object chosen to be stored in the root node should be the best splitter of the whole object set P. The object chosen to be stored in an internal tree node T should be the best splitter of the corresponding subset P .

The best splitter is chosen to be the object with respect to which the other objects spread evenly. For example, in Figure 5, the α-polygon of the tree node Ti contains seven objects. If we choose the object p1 as the splitter, most other objects allocate in the upper-left sub- polygon (Figure 5a). However, if we choose the object p2 as the splitter, the other objects spread more evenly around p2 (Figure 5b). Further, if we rotate the split lines slightly, every sub-polygon contains the same number of objects (Figure 5c). This layout of the split lines is optimal w.r.t. p2. Let us define the optimal layout of the split lines. In this section, we pro- pose a tree-based algorithm, which updates the vacancy ranges while processing objects and avoids processing the objects (i.e., camera sensors) that cannot influence the vacancy ranges. At the beginning, the algorithm sets the vacancy ranges V to be [0◦, 360◦), and accordingly it sets the occupied ranges C to be ∅. The C is the complementary set of V, i.e., C = [0◦, 360◦) − V. The algorithm visits the tree nodes from the root node, and descends to the child node if the child node contains the cameras that may influence C. The algo- rithm enlarges C according to the objects visited. The algorithm terminates when C becomes [0◦, 360◦) or there is no tree node remained unvisited. Notice that in this section we assume that all the objects P in the tree are the cameras that can see the target q. 4.1 Occupied range enlargements In this section, we discuss what objects can enlarge the occupied ranges C. First, we define the occupied ranges C formally. Definition 9 (Occupied Direction) Given a target point q, if a direction ωi ∈ [0◦, 360◦) can cover at least one object, it is an occupied direction. of an occupied direction is larger than zero. Definition 10 (Occupied Direction Range) Given a target point q, a range C ∈ [0◦, 360◦) is an occupied direction range, if any direction ω ∈ C is an occupied direction.

According to Definition 9 and 10, the occupied direction is opposite of the vacant direc- tion, and the occupied range is opposite of the vacant range. The result of a vacancy query is a set of vacancy ranges (V), and equiently, the result is also the complementary set of the occupied ranges (C), i.e., where U is the whole direction range [0◦, 360◦). An object p can enlarge C by a maximum of 2θ degrees, which are the length of the influence range of p. The influence range of p is the angular range [φp ↓ θ, φp ↑ θ ]. For simple, we denote the influence range as [φ+ p , φ− ]. In the influence range of p, any direction can cover p and thus the direction is occupied. Most of the time, p cannot enlarge C by the maximum, but can enlarge C fewer degrees, because its influence range may overlap with the current C, which is obtained after visiting the preceding objects of p. Sometimes, p cannot even enlarge C at all. Specially, if p is the first object visited, it can enlarge C by the maximum, since C is empty at the beginning. Let us consider (1) what objects cannot enlarge C, (2) what objects can enlarge C by few degrees (i.e., smaller than 2θ); (3) what objects can make two occupied ranges merge, where (3) is a special case of (2); (4) what objects can enlarge C by the maximum degrees (i.e., 2θ ). Next, we implement the vacancy query algorithm based on the α-polygon tree. The algo- rithm maintains the occupied range set C, the pruning range set W, and a queue which contains the unvisited tree nodes. At the beginning, the root node of the tree is pushed into the queue. The set C is initialized to be the influence range of the object stored in the root node. At each iteration, the algorithm visits the top element T and gets the objects stored in T ’s child nodes. Let p refers to the object stored in a child node. The algorithm checks whether p is in the pruning ranges W. If it is not, the algorithm updates C according to Theorem 3 and Theorem 6. Specially, the algorithm merges two occupied ranges if the con- dition in Theorem 5 is satisfied. After updating C, the algorithm decides which child nodes could be pushed into the queue. It is not necessary to visit the child nodes that are covered by W. The reason is in Lemma 1. Lemma 1 The object p cannot enlarge the occupied ranges C, if p is in the sub-tree rooted at T , which is a tree node covered by the pruning ranges W. According to Lemma 1, the algorithm will not visit the tree nodes in the sub-tree rooted at T if they are fully covered by W, however, the tree nodes, which cannot be fully covered by W, will be pushed into the queue for later visits. After pushing the child nodes, the top element T is popped out of the queue. The algorithm terminates when the queue becomes empty or when C becomes [0◦, 360◦). Algorithm 6 introduces the function UpdateRange(), which is used to update C and W when checking an object p. We maintain a variable oper to indicate different cases. At line 1, we initialize oper to be 0. From line 2 to 12, we identify the case and set oper. The foreach loop is to find where φp falls into. If φp is in the update range of an occupied range Ci, we should further check whether it is in the update range of the next range Ci+1. If φp is in the two update ranges, we set oper to 2 (line 5). If φp is only in one update range, we set oper to 1 (line 7). If φp is in the pruning range of Ci, we should break the loop because p cannot influence C nor W (lines 10 to 11). From line 13 to 22, we do different operations according to oper. Ifoper = 0, it means that p does not fall in any update ranges nor fall in any pruning range, and thus it can contribute a new occupied range (φ+ p ) (lines 13 to 15). If oper = 1, it means that p can enlarge only one occupied range Ci, and the corresponding pruning range Wi should be enlarged too (lines 16 to 17). If oper = 2, it means that p can influence two neighbor occupied ranges Ci and Ci+1, and thus we merge Ci and Ci+1 and also merge Wi and Wi+1 (lines 18 to 19). At last, we obtain new C and W according to p. The maximum number of occupied ranges is 360/(2θ ), and thus the time complexity of Algorithm 6 is O(1). Time complexity analysis In Algorithm 5, the while loop (lines 4 to 16) repeats n times in the worst case, where n is the number of tree nodes. In the while loop, the two foreach loops (lines 6 to 9, lines 10 to 15) repeats m times respectively, where m is the num- ber of child nodes of each tree node. Thus, in the worst case, the time complexity of the Figure 9 Example of the progressive algorithm

progressive approach is O(n) since m is a small constant number. The worst case happens when the target locates in the fringe areas of cameras, while the best case happens when the target locates in the center areas of cameras. In the best case, the algorithm can termi- nate early because the occupied range can reach [0◦, 360◦) soon with the complexity O(1). The progressive approach (Algorithm 5) is more efficient than the baseline approach (Algo- rithm 1) for three reasons. (1) The progressive approach can reduce the search space by pruning the tree nodes that contain useless objects. The useless objects are the objects that cannot enlarge the current occupied ranges. For example, in FigureFigure 9d, we prune the tree node T3. (2) The progressive approach can terminate quite early if the occupied ranges have become the whole range [0◦, 360◦) (See line 8 in Algorithm 5.). However, the baseline approach cannot terminate before having checked all objects. (3) The progressive approach takes the advantage of the checking order of the objects. The child nodes of a tree node T spread around the object p in T . It ensures that we can enlarge the occupied ranges as much as possible. However, the baseline approach does not arrange the checking order of objects. We use synthetic and real datasets to evaluate the performances of α-polygon trees and vacancy queries. As Table 1 shows, the synthetic datasets are P100, P1K , P2K P10K , and P100K , which contain 100, 103, 2 × 103, 104, and 105 points, respectively. The synthetic datasets are generated randomly in a two-dimensional 100 × 100 space. The real datasets are Parea1 , Parea2 , and Parea3 , which are the camera positions in the Safe City Project of Qinhuangdao China [1]. The datasets Parea1 , Parea2 , and Parea3 contain the positions of 499 cameras in area1, and the positions of 262 cameras in area2, and the positions of 184 cameras in area3. We convert the geographical coordinates (i.e, longitude and latitude) of these cameras to coordinates in a two-dimensional 100 × 100 space. Due to security concerns the area names are shown as area1, area2 and area3 instead of their real names. All the experiments are conducted on a machine with an Intel Core i5- 2415M CPU with 4 GB of memory running Windows 7 (32 bit). All the algorithms proposed are implemented in C++. We did not show the performances of opt-tree- based on P10K and P100K because building optimized tree on large datasets cost plenty of time. The number of objects pruned grows when the data size increases. The reason is that the density of objects increases with the data size. We evaluate the performances of the vacancy queries when the parameter θ varies. We conduct the experiments on the synthetic dataset P1K and the real dataset Parea1 . The time costs of tree-based and opt-tree-based decrease with the enlargement of θ . The reason is that the tree-based algorithms can prune more objects when θ is larger. We conduct experiments on both synthetic dataset P10K and P100 and real datasets Parea1 and Parea2 , when θ varies in six different degrees, i.e., {20◦, 25◦, 30◦, 35◦, 40◦, 45◦}. Figure 18 shows the experimental results. The full-occupied rate increases with θ on smaller datasets, i.e., P100 and Parea2 which contains 262 points. For a direction ω ∈ [0◦, 360◦), it is easier to cover some objects when θ is larger. Thus, the number of full-occupied query points increases with θ . In this paper, we propose the vacancy query in CSNs. Given a target q, the vacancy query can find the vacant direction ranges where q cannot be recognized by any camera even if the cameras can see q. To support the vacancy query, we design the α-polygon tree, which can organize the objects according to their directions. We also propose an algorithm to make the tree as balance as possible. Based on the α-polygon tree, we design a tree-based approach to answer the vacancy queries. The experimental results show that our proposed approach can answer the queries correctly and efficiently. 1. C.
